<subsection xml:id="subsec-indices">
    <title>Indices</title>
    <introduction>
    <title>Introduction</title>

        <p>
            Mathematics involves working with very large and very small numbers, which can be simplified using indices. An <m>index</m> (plural <m>indices</m>) also called <m>exponent</m> or <m>power</m> is a way of writing repeated multiplication of the same number. 
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Why Are Indices Important?</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            Indices are widely used in:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Scientific notation writing, where numbers are sometimes very large and sometimes very small, such as the speed of light or the size of an atom.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Physics and Engineering to understand exponential growth and decay rates, such as radioactive decay and population growth.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Finance and money in calculating compound interest.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

    </introduction>


    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-express-numbers-in-index-form">
        <title>Expressing Numbers in Index Form</title>
        <p>
            <term>Introduction</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            Numbers can be written in different ways. One useful way is index notation (exponential form), which helps in simplifying calculations and representing very large or small numbers efficiently. In this section, you will learn how to express numbers using indices and understand their significance in mathematics.
        </p>
        <p>
            Consider having:
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                2^3 = 2 \times 2 \times 2
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                = 8
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            In this case <m>2</m> is the base, 3 is the index, and we get <m>8</m> as the solution.
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore given <m>x</m> as a whole number;
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>
                x^a = x \times x \times x</m> .......(<m>a </m> is the number of times <m>x</m> is repeated)
            
        </p>
        <p>
            Example:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>a^2</m> = <m>a \times a</m>  (<m>a</m>  repeated twice)
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2^3</m> = <m>2 \times 2 \times 2</m>  (<m>2</m>  repeated thrice)
        </p>
        <p>
            <m> = 8</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>5^4</m> = <m>5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5</m>  (<m>5</m>  repeated four times)
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>= 625</m>
        </p>
    </subsubsection>


